\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.1}{\ignorespaces Comparing Chain-of-Thought (CoT) and ReAct reasoning. \textbf {Left:} CoT lays out a chain of reasoning, then answers. \textbf {Right:} ReAct interleaves reasoning with actions, letting models pull in information and adapt on the fly.}}{12}{figure.caption.16}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.2}{\ignorespaces Evolution of autonomous agents from 2022 to 2025. Research unfolded across four eras: \textbf {Foundation} (RLHF methods established), \textbf {Emergence} (agents acquire tool-calling and multi-step reasoning), \textbf {Scaling} (benchmarks proliferate, code/GUI agents mature), and \textbf {Autonomy} (GRPO unlocks lean self-improvement loops, with some tasks now rivaling human scores).}}{17}{figure.caption.19}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.1}{\ignorespaces Three-stage training for agentic systems. \textbf {Stage 1:} A base model supplies language understanding. \textbf {Stage 2:} Imitation learning on 5K--10K examples drills task formats. \textbf {Stage 3:} RL tunes the policy through environment interaction, letting agents cope with novel situations outside their training distribution.}}{34}{figure.caption.82}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.2}{\ignorespaces The reinforcement learning loop. At each timestep, the \textbf {agent} observes state $s_t$, selects action $a_t$ according to policy $\pi _\theta $, and receives reward $r_t$ from the \textbf {environment}. We want a policy that racks up as much long-run reward as possible. In the agentic setting, the ``environment'' spans web browsers, code interpreters, operating systems, and API back-ends.}}{35}{figure.caption.83}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.3}{\ignorespaces Taxonomy of 19 RL research categories organized into five clusters: \textbf {Core Algorithms} (policy/value/model-based methods), \textbf {Learning Paradigms} (how agents acquire behavior), \textbf {Advanced Methods} (multi-agent, hierarchical, safe exploration), \textbf {Applications} (domain-specific implementations), and \textbf {Infrastructure} (frameworks, benchmarks, surveys). Arrows indicate foundational dependencies.}}{38}{figure.caption.84}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.4}{\ignorespaces Value-based methods learn $Q(s,a)$ and derive policy via $\arg \max $; policy-based methods directly parameterize $\pi _\theta (a|s)$ and sample actions stochastically.}}{38}{figure.caption.85}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.5}{\ignorespaces Hierarchical RL: manager policy selects subgoals every $k$ steps; worker policy executes primitive actions to achieve them. Temporal abstraction reduces effective horizon.}}{39}{figure.caption.86}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.6}{\ignorespaces Exploration via intrinsic motivation: curiosity rewards ($r_i$) supplement sparse external rewards ($r_e$), enabling learning in hard-exploration domains.}}{40}{figure.caption.87}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.7}{\ignorespaces Model-based RL loop: learn dynamics model from real experience, then use imagined rollouts for planning, cutting data requirements 10--100$\times $.}}{40}{figure.caption.88}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.8}{\ignorespaces Meta-RL: learn initialization $\theta $ that enables fast adaptation to new tasks with few gradient steps. Outer loop optimizes ``learning to learn.''}}{41}{figure.caption.89}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.9}{\ignorespaces Distribution of reinforcement learning algorithms across 80\ cataloged method variants (2024--2025). GRPO and its offshoots now lead the pack, a sign that the community has pivoted toward RAM-friendly training pipelines that allow bigger models to fit on the same hardware.}}{46}{figure.caption.91}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.10}{\ignorespaces Radar comparison of PPO, DPO, and GRPO across six dimensions (scale: 1--5, higher is better). GRPO lands in the sweet spot---low RAM footprint yet strong results---while PPO shines at exploration and DPO at stability and data efficiency. This visualization explains why GRPO now dominates in GPU-limited labs.}}{48}{figure.caption.93}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.11}{\ignorespaces Algorithm selection decision tree. Start with infrastructure constraints (memory), then consider reward availability and exploration needs.}}{50}{figure.caption.94}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.12}{\ignorespaces Outcome supervision vs process supervision for reasoning tasks. \textbf {Left:} Outcome-only rewards evaluate the final answer, potentially rewarding flawed reasoning that happens to land on the right conclusion. \textbf {Right:} Process supervision gives step-level feedback, validating every step of the reasoning process. Research has shown that step-level reward models typically exceed the performance of outcome-based models on MATH, with the gap widening as sampling budgets increase---sound reasoning chains generalize better to new problems. }}{53}{figure.caption.96}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces How agentic workflows connect LLM-based logic, tool integration, environment feedback, and memory. The agent sharpens its actions step by step based on what it observes.}}{55}{figure.caption.97}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces Cross-attention mechanism in vision-language agents. \textbf {Left:} The visual module converts image patches into embeddings $\mathbf {v}_i$. \textbf {Right:} The text module converts tokens into embeddings $\mathbf {t}_i$. \textbf {Center:} Cross-attention uses text as queries (Q) and visual features as keys/values (K, V), enabling the model to locate the visual region corresponding to ``search button.'' This architecture underlies GUI automation systems like CogAgent~\cite {hong2023cogagent} and SeeClick~\cite {cheng2024seeclick}, achieving 89--96\% grounding accuracy.}}{57}{figure.caption.98}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.3}{\ignorespaces Performance gap between GPT-4 and humans on agentic benchmarks. \textbf {SWE-bench} tests code repair on real GitHub issues; \textbf {WebArena} checks web navigation (booking, shopping); \textbf {OSWorld} evaluates desktop automation requiring vision and control. The large gap (GPT-4 at 1.7--14.4\% vs. humans at 35--78\%) shows how hard autonomous multi-step execution is and motivates RL-based fine-tuning.}}{58}{figure.caption.99}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.4}{\ignorespaces Training method comparison across agentic benchmarks (December 2025). Each benchmark shows three approaches: \textbf {Baseline} (prompting-only methods), \textbf {SFT} (supervised fine-tuning on demonstrations), and \textbf {RL} (reinforcement learning with GRPO or PPO). The trend is consistent: RL-based approaches are associated with substantial gains across all benchmarks, with AIME 2024 showing the most dramatic improvement (9.3\% $\rightarrow $ 79.8\%, an 8.6$\times $ increase via DeepSeek-R1's GRPO training).}}{59}{figure.caption.101}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.5}{\ignorespaces Benchmark improvement trajectories across five major agentic benchmarks (2023--2025). The transition from prompting to SFT coincided with modest gains, while the period of RL adoption (especially GRPO) in 2024--2025 is associated with dramatic improvements. AIME 2024 shows the most striking trajectory, reaching 79.8\%.}}{60}{figure.caption.102}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces How Retrieval-Augmented Generation grounds knowledge. Given a query, the system pulls Top-K relevant chunks from a knowledge base using hybrid search (BM25 + dense embeddings). Retrieved context merges with the query and feeds into the language model. This curbs hallucination and lets the system tap into current facts beyond its training cutoff, boosting factual accuracy 15--30\% on knowledge-heavy tasks.}}{64}{figure.caption.105}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces Decentralized multi-agent architecture showing independent agents (1-4) coordinating through message passing (dashed lines) while interacting with a shared environment. Each agent operates independently while coordinating through messages. All agents interact with a shared environment, so multiple workers can run side-by-side and specialize (e.g., Agent 1: planning, Agent 2: coding, Agent 3: testing). Spreading out the control logic avoids bottlenecks and lets coordination patterns emerge organically.}}{66}{figure.caption.106}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.1}{\ignorespaces Experiment campaign: 44 total runs across Tinker Cloud, Modal H100, and local platforms.}}{71}{figure.caption.107}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.2}{\ignorespaces GRPO training curves on GSM8K across model scales (from W\&B).}}{72}{figure.caption.109}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.3}{\ignorespaces GRPO training pipeline: prompts are sampled, $G$ completions generated per prompt, rewards computed, group-relative advantages normalized, and policy updated.}}{72}{figure.caption.110}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.4}{\ignorespaces PPO training curves on GSM8K --- Qwen3-8B and Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct (Modal H100, from W\&B).}}{73}{figure.caption.112}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.5}{\ignorespaces Algorithm selection is model-dependent: GRPO wins on Qwen3-8B (+11.9\,pp) while PPO dominates on Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct (+13.1\,pp).}}{73}{figure.caption.113}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.6}{\ignorespaces Full 76-run reward heatmap from the World-Class and Bitter Lesson campaigns, highlighting the 17$\times $ gap between Tinker GRPO and TRL GRPO on matched models.}}{76}{figure.caption.116}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.1}{\ignorespaces Frontier model GRPO training on GSM8K (from W\&B).}}{78}{figure.caption.120}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.2}{\ignorespaces Structural ceiling: GRPO performance decreases as tasks shift from format compliance to semantic reasoning.}}{79}{figure.caption.122}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.3}{\ignorespaces Cross-architecture GRPO comparison --- GPT-OSS-20B and Kimi-K2 (from W\&B).}}{80}{figure.caption.123}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.4}{\ignorespaces Size ladder: below $\sim $8B-instruct, GRPO yields zero learning across both model families. A sharp capacity threshold exists between 3B and 8B.}}{80}{figure.caption.125}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.5}{\ignorespaces Wave 2 group size ablation --- $G \in \{2, 4, 16, 32\}$ on Qwen3-8B (from W\&B).}}{81}{figure.caption.127}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.6}{\ignorespaces Wave 6 sensitivity ablation --- temperature, LoRA rank, batch size on Qwen3-8B (from W\&B).}}{82}{figure.caption.128}%
