\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {14.1}{\ignorespaces Illustrative training curves comparing PPO, DPO, and GRPO on agentic benchmarks. Based on trends reported in \cite {deepseek2025r1, rafailov2023direct}, GRPO typically converges faster and reaches higher task success on verifiable tasks because its lighter memory footprint lets practitioners crank up batch sizes.}}{106}{figure.caption.158}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {14.2}{\ignorespaces GSM8K training curves for all four models. Qwen3-8B (base) demonstrates a characteristic RL emergence/phase transition around steps 22--25, jumping from $\sim $13\% to $\sim $78\% in five steps before saturating at 100\%. Llama-3.2-3B (dashed) is the negative result: reward never exceeds 2\% because the model lacks the minimum capacity to generate any correct solutions, leaving GRPO with no positive signal to learn from.}}{112}{figure.caption.160}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {14.3}{\ignorespaces MATH competition benchmark results (ongoing). The gap between GSM8K (100\% for Qwen3-8B) and MATH ($\sim $14\%) reveals a substantial difficulty cliff. The instruct model achieves 50--87\% but with high variance, reflecting the heterogeneous difficulty of competition problems (AMC algebra vs.\ AIME geometry).}}{113}{figure.caption.161}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {14.4}{\ignorespaces GRPO training pipeline. The Atropos Environment samples prompts from the dataset and forwards batches to the Rollout Server (vLLM), which generates $G$ completions per prompt. The Environment scores each completion (binary reward) and passes trajectory--reward pairs to the Tinker Trainer, which performs the GRPO policy gradient update over LoRA parameters. Updated weights are checkpointed and reloaded into the Rollout Server every $N$ steps for on-policy training.}}{114}{figure.caption.162}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
